node.text:
“Families have all shapes and colors.”

CDR Hale Allegretti, the waterways management division chief at U. S. Coast Guard Sector San Francisco, speaks about the importance of being able to serve openly as #LGBTQ during his time in the military.

Allegretti, a #transgender service member, joined the U.S. Coast Guard under the Don’t Ask, Don’t Tell policy, which prohibited members from disclosing their orientation.

“Don’t Ask, Don’t Tell impacted me because I always felt like there was a wall of secrecy between me and my shipmates,” said Allegretti.

The Don’t Ask, Don’t Tell Repeal Act of 2010 ended the policy, thus allowing #LGBTQ people to serve openly in the United States Armed Forces.

“When you can put words to what you’re feeling and what you’re seeing and be supported by the people around you, to feel respected, to feel like you can serve in a safe place, there’s really no way to measure it,” said Allegretti. “It’s incredible.”

#PrideMonth #RepresentationMatters

Video by Petty Officer 2nd Class Brandon Giles U.S. Coast Guard Pacific Southwest

Nothing like conning a ship at 14 knots only 160 feet away from a fuel tanker, fill’er up!
•
Fueling at Sea (FAS) allows MUNRO to remain in the operational area without returning to port to refuel. FASing is more convenient and 8-10x faster than refueling with a fuel truck at a pier. 
•
Thank you to our @usnavy partners and the USNS John Lenthall (T-AO-189) for the assist!

This video highlights CGC MUNRO’s most recent Eastern Pacific counter drug patrol where the crew were protecting our national security in the midst of the pandemic. The Coast Guard and MUNRO continue to deter transnational organized criminals in pursuit of justice.  
•
MUNRO and attached Helicopter Interdiction Tactical Squadron (HITRON) were responsible for 20 boardings, 12 interdictions and seized a total of 16,265 lbs of cocaine and 11,650 lbs of marijuana with a combined wholesale value of $334 million.

node.text:
U.S. Coast Guard Cutter Campbell deploys to the Arctic in support of the search and rescue exercise SAREX ARGUS hosted by the Joint Arctic Command, alongside allies Denmark, France and the U.S. Navy. CGC Campbell assisted NOAA and the International Ice Patrol deploying 13 weather buoys and giving feedback on the ice state throughout Arctic waters. CGC Campbell and her crew earned the Arctic Service Medal for their deployment which was a historic first as this was the furthest north a medium endurance cutter has journeyed into the Atlantic Arctic. 

U.S. Coast Guard video by SN Kate Kilroy and CGC Campbell 
Music by ENS Middleton

node.text: Fun Fact: USCGC SWORDFISH’s hull number begins with an 87 to identify its length. In fact, if a platform in the Coast Guard in 99 feet or less, it’s first two numbers identify a length. Also, the term “Cutter” identifies a Coast Guard vessel 65 feet or greater, with accommodations to live aboard. In our case that’s berthings for 11 crewmembers!  #uscg #semperparatus #pnw #searchandrescue

node.text: Welcome aboard USCGC SWORDFISH (WPB-87358)! We are an 87-foot Coastal Patrol Boat based out of Port Angeles, WA on the Olympic Peninsula. Our Area of Responsibility stretches from the border with Canada’s Vancouver Island all the way to Southern Oregon and includes the Strait of Juan de Fuca. We have an 11-person crew. Since being commissioned in 2005 USCGC SWORDFISH has primarily been focusing on Search and Rescue, Living Marine Resources, Ports, Waterways, and Coastal Security (PWCS), Fisheries, and Maritime Law Enforcement. Be sure to follow along this weekend to get a glimpse of life onboard the USCGC SWORDFISH and how we support the Coast Guard’s missions in the Pacific Northwest!  #USCG #coastguard #coastguardrescue

node.text: Thank you all for joining us this weekend for USCGC JOHN MCCORMICK’s takeover! We are grateful for having this opportunity to share what we do each day to support Coast Guard missions, and we hoped you enjoyed learning about our amazing crew and cutter!

node.text: One of JOHN MCCORMICK’s primary missions is Maritime Law Enforcement. To that end, we work hard to enforce laws that protect Alaska’s mariners, resources, infrastructure, and environment. We team up closely with interagency and international partners, including NOAA and the Canadian Coast Guard, to conduct vessel boardings, patrol maritime zones, and coordinate response efforts. Together, we embody our ship’s motto: Stewards of the Last Frontier!

node.text: JOHN MCCORMICK’s crew is a tight-knit team. Our Machinery Technicians and Electrician Mates ensure our engines, generators, and installed systems continue running in harsh conditions; our Damage Controlman trains each of us to do our part when responding to emergencies; our Electronics Technicians support all of our electronics and communication systems; our Boatswain Mates operate our small boat, navigate, and conduct Law Enforcement; and our Culinary Specialists prepare three meals a day, including our very favorite Taco Tuesday lunches. Each person consistently goes beyond expectations to help MCCORMICK set the standard for the fleet!

node.text: As a Fast Response Cutter, JOHN MCCORMICK has the ability to launch its Over The Horizon cutter boat from the stern. This allows us to quickly and efficiently get our small boat underway and on scene. Our boat crew usually consists of a Coxswain, Engineer, Boarding Officer, and Boarding Team Member, all of whom work together to conduct law enforcement, search and rescue, and personnel transfer operations. To ensure their comfort and endurance in Alaska’s harsh climate, the small boat team is always outfitted with life jackets, drysuits, and most importantly… snacks!

node.text: Earlier this summer, CGC JOHN MCCORMICK had the opportunity to patrol in Washington and Oregon, where we spent our days boarding fishing and recreational vessels. One of the most interesting parts of our patrol was visiting Seattle! To get there, we sailed through the Chittenden Locks and Montlake Cut. The channel into the city was one of the narrowest that our bridge team had ever transited- we really grew as a team!

node.text: USCGC JOHN MCCORMICK’s area of responsibility stretches over 400 nautical miles and encompasses all of Southeast Alaska. Believe it or not, our AOR is larger than the entire state of Florida! We are lucky to have some of the most beautiful views in the country: sailing between soaring mountains, we encounter humpback whales, orcas, otters and seals. We can also spot bighorn sheep, black bears, and bald eagles-sometimes, we even see the northern lights! Many of the Coasties stationed in Ketchikan consider it one of the best locations in the Coast Guard.

node.text:
Life onboard CGC JOHN MCCORMICK is dynamic and exciting. As a patrol boat, we remain ready to respond to distress calls or complete tasking from District 17 at a moment’s notice. During a typical day, our bridge team safely navigates the ship, our engineers conduct rounds to inspect the machinery, and our Culinary Specialists prepare the food that we eat together on the mess deck. With a crew of 26 people, we’re able to get to know one another personally and establish strong working relationships, which directly translates to our teamwork when running all-hands evolutions like pulling into port or practicing emergency response procedures. 

Head to our story if you want to learn more about CGC JOHN MCCORMICK!
